In my view, we use the term God too loosely. There are =
Mahatmas, great Mahatmas, fantastic spiritual beings, and then there is God=
. Buddha was a fantastic and super-duper spiritual being.

Now coming to yo=
ur question, there is no fixed rule of how and what can lead a man to liber=
ation or higher states of spirituality. Frankly, there is no path which *gu=
arantees* liberation. All paths have the potential, but realization is an i=
ndividual's journey, and each such journey will not be a mirror of anyone e=
lse's journey. Broadly there may be similarities, but nuances will differ. =
For some it is necessary to leave their wife and children to be spiritual, =
for others they may not need to do so. 

Infact, the aim of sadhana is to p=
repare yourself. If and when you experience and realize God, it is going be=
 God's sweet will. Sadhana does not guarantee realization, but without sadh=
ana it is nearly impossibly, for you are simply not prepared enough to expe=
rience. 

