The idea of trying to =
force a cause effect relation to everything is an inherent tendency of the =
mind. It is not necessarily how things are. Neither is it useful.

If a man=
 wants to only experience God, then every life-experience, apparently good =
or apparently bad, is only going to take your forward towards the goal if y=
ou keep your aim fixed. No wonder Lord Krishna stresses so much on detachme=
nt and equanimity in his advice to Arjuna, rather than trying to find out c=
ause-effect relationships of the apparently good or the apparently bad kind=
s. 

Sufferings are a great way of focusing on God. Really. Slowly but sure=
ly you realize that the world will run in its own pattern and you cannot do=
 much about it, except control what is in your power to control, that is yo=
ur internal state. 

Krishna gives this advice to Arjuna in the Second Chap=
ter: "Dukhesva Anudhvigna-manah Sukhesu-Vigatasprhah Vita-Raga-Bhaya-Krodha=
h Sthita-Dhira Munir Uchyate" Gita 2:56 [Miseries do not agitate the mind, =
in sukha (fleeting happiness) there is no elation, such a one who is free f=
rom attachment, fear and anger, is a sage of steady mind.]

Tough? Sure. Bu=
t no harm in making an effort. This is something to be tried on a regular b=
asis, day in and day out.

